<h2>Where this fits in the unit</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Block 4 (Scale of the Cosmos)</strong> — first introduction. Load Earth / Mars / Venus, then change the host-star type to see the habitable zone shrink dramatically around M-dwarfs.</li>
  <li><strong>Block 6 (Choose Your Exoplanet)</strong> — load your candidate's preset. Notice how Atmosphere = Unknown propagates as UNCERTAIN through the framework — that's <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL</a> in action.</li>
  <li><strong>Block 7 (Habitability Framework)</strong> — switch to <strong>Compare</strong> mode (Earth + Mars + your exoplanet). The 6-row framework readout becomes the spine of your <a href="/units/unit-1/assessment-goldilocks-report/">Goldilocks Report</a> framework section.</li>
  <li><strong>Block 8 (Drafting Day)</strong> — click <strong>Copy as JSON</strong> or <strong>Download JSON</strong> in Compare mode. The export's "For your AI Documentation Template" section satisfies the K/U gate without extra documentation work.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Before you start</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Have your <a href="/units/unit-1/assessment-goldilocks-report/">Goldilocks Report</a> open — Steps 2 (framework) and 3 (compare across cases) are what the calculator's Compare mode supports.</li>
  <li>Skim the calculator's <strong>Show assumptions</strong> drawer before trusting any verdict. The K/U gate on the rubric requires you OPVL the calculator itself.</li>
  <li>Pair with the <a href="/ai-partners/planet-hunter/">Planet Hunter</a> — the calculator computes; the Planet Hunter helps you reason about what the numbers mean.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Teacher links</h2>

<p>Bookmark these to deep-link students into a specific preset or compare loadout:</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>?preset=trappist1e</code> — opens Explore with TRAPPIST-1 e loaded</li>
  <li><code>?preset=kepler22b</code> — opens the Block 8 worked-example planet</li>
  <li><code>?compare=earth,mars,trappist1e</code> — opens Compare mode with the default Goldilocks loadout</li>
  <li><code>?compare=earth,mars,k218b</code> — Compare with K2-18 b as the chosen exoplanet</li>
</ul>

